WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.878
CHARLES:
Welcome to our killer reveal party,

00:02.878 --> 00:05.964
where we will reveal Bunny's killer.

00:05.964 --> 00:07.716
- We've been on to you
since this afternoon.

00:07.716 --> 00:09.551
- I just wanted Cinda to notice me.

00:09.551 --> 00:10.552
[echoing click]

00:10.552 --> 00:13.597
CHARLES:
With that, another mystery solved. Wow.

00:13.597 --> 00:15.766
Two murders back-to-back.
- Yep.

00:15.766 --> 00:17.351
- You're actually renovating.

00:17.351 --> 00:20.229
MABEL: Well, it is about time.
CHARLES: Hey, Joy.

00:20.229 --> 00:22.439
- Are you asking me out on a date?

00:22.439 --> 00:23.690
- Yes.

00:23.690 --> 00:25.108
♪

00:25.108 --> 00:26.109
OLIVER:
Broadway?

00:26.109 --> 00:28.111
I think I-I would be perfect for that.

00:28.111 --> 00:29.655
And who's the star?

00:29.655 --> 00:31.740
[knocking]
Ben?

00:31.740 --> 00:33.617
Everyone gets opening night jitters!

00:33.617 --> 00:35.244
♪

00:35.244 --> 00:37.329
- I'm good!
- Fasten your seat belts.

00:37.329 --> 00:39.248
[applause]

00:39.248 --> 00:43.001
- What turned me into
a creature of the night?

00:43.001 --> 00:44.837
[birds chirping]

00:44.837 --> 00:45.921
[thud]

00:45.921 --> 00:47.798
[audience gasping]
OLIVER: Somebody! Anybody!

00:47.798 --> 00:49.174
CHARLES:
He's not moving!

00:49.174 --> 00:51.051
[murmuring]
WOMAN: Ben! Call 911!

00:51.051 --> 00:53.679
- You've gotta be fucking kidding me.

00:53.679 --> 00:55.806
♪

00:56.849 --> 00:59.852
♪ orchestral music playing ♪

00:59.852 --> 01:02.855
[audience chatter]

01:03.814 --> 01:05.482
[curtains click, rattle]

01:05.482 --> 01:07.985
CHARLES:
All the world's a stage

01:09.236 --> 01:12.865
and all the blah, blah, blah.
We all know how that one goes.

01:13.615 --> 01:15.492
But if you are a theatrical type,

01:15.492 --> 01:17.327
there's a good chance you became smitten

01:17.327 --> 01:19.079
at a very young age.

01:19.538 --> 01:24.877
- ♪ The sweetest sounds I'll ever hear ♪

01:24.877 --> 01:28.839
♪ Are still inside my head ♪

01:28.839 --> 01:30.340
CHARLES:
Seeing the wonders of a life

01:30.340 --> 01:33.427
you might be part of one day,

01:33.427 --> 01:35.554
full of stories and experiences

01:35.554 --> 01:39.349
you can only dream about
from the eighth row,

01:39.349 --> 01:41.894
behind two beehives in row seven.

01:41.894 --> 01:47.399
- ♪ The most entrancing sight of all ♪

01:47.399 --> 01:52.905
♪ Is yet for me to see ♪

01:52.905 --> 01:55.824
♪ And the dearest love ♪

01:55.824 --> 01:59.536
♪ In all the world ♪

01:59.536 --> 02:03.498
♪ Is waiting somewhere for me ♪

02:04.124 --> 02:06.919
♪ Is waiting ♪

02:06.919 --> 02:08.629
♪ Somewhere ♪

02:08.629 --> 02:12.591
♪ Somewhere for me ♪

02:12.591 --> 02:16.553
♪ orchestral music continues ♪

02:19.890 --> 02:21.892
CHARLES:
Once smitten though,

02:21.892 --> 02:23.894
then comes the work.

02:24.645 --> 02:26.647
Of classes and training...

02:26.647 --> 02:28.065
♪

02:28.065 --> 02:30.067
of speech and technique...

02:31.401 --> 02:32.778
honing your craft,

02:32.778 --> 02:35.906
as you pound the pavement
in New York City,

02:35.906 --> 02:39.034
auditioning for anything and everything,

02:39.034 --> 02:41.995
all in pursuit of that
moment in the spotlight

02:41.995 --> 02:45.123
where you hope someone might see you,

02:45.123 --> 02:48.919
really see you,
and say those magic words.

02:48.919 --> 02:51.129
"Where have you been?"

02:52.714 --> 02:56.218
But what if those magic words never come?

02:56.218 --> 02:58.595
And it's only rejection,

02:58.595 --> 03:01.390
over and over again,

03:01.390 --> 03:03.350
year after year,

03:03.350 --> 03:06.061
and near miss after near miss,

03:06.061 --> 03:09.189
until you realize that near miss

03:09.189 --> 03:11.191
has become your life.

03:12.526 --> 03:16.446
How do you keep at it with any hope?

03:16.446 --> 03:18.615
♪

03:20.367 --> 03:22.160
CASTING DIRECTOR:
Thank you, very nice.

03:22.160 --> 03:24.204
So, someone's shown up

03:24.204 --> 03:26.874
who's not on our list,
maybe a walk-in.

03:27.833 --> 03:30.836
I do know her. She's capable,

03:30.836 --> 03:33.964
a little vanilla, but we've got
about 10 minutes until lunch...

03:34.506 --> 03:36.049
- Yeah, sure. [sniffs]

03:36.049 --> 03:37.801
CASTING DIRECTOR:
Ready, Durkin, you still there?

03:37.801 --> 03:39.970
LORETTA DURKIN: Yes!
[script rustling]

03:39.970 --> 03:42.139
Yes! Hi!

03:42.139 --> 03:44.600
Oh, hi. I-I'm so sorry, I thought...

03:44.600 --> 03:47.603
My agent assured me
that I was on the list...

03:47.603 --> 03:48.896
CASTING DIRECTOR: It's fine.

03:48.896 --> 03:50.606
Do you have the pages
for the role of the nanny?

03:51.231 --> 03:54.276
- Y-- Uh, yes. Is it just the one scene?

03:54.276 --> 03:56.486
CASTING DIRECTOR: That's right.
Whenever you're ready.

03:56.486 --> 03:57.487
[sighs]

03:57.487 --> 03:59.489
[script quietly crinkling]

03:59.990 --> 04:01.825
- [huffs] Enough!

04:01.825 --> 04:04.328
Enough of your questions, Detective.

04:05.537 --> 04:08.749
I'm happy to tell you
who I am and what it is I do

04:08.749 --> 04:11.919
without your insistent... probing.

04:15.088 --> 04:17.799
I am a caretaker of children,

04:17.799 --> 04:20.010
to whom I'm given charge.

04:20.010 --> 04:23.847
Am I a substitute
for the child's true mother?

04:24.264 --> 04:25.265
[inhales]

04:26.391 --> 04:29.603
Some would prefer I say no,
but I believe...

04:30.479 --> 04:33.482
I am. I must be...

04:34.733 --> 04:37.236
their mother when it's only me with them.

04:38.278 --> 04:39.905
Because

04:39.905 --> 04:42.658
a child needs to feel, at all times,

04:42.658 --> 04:43.909
safe.

04:43.909 --> 04:47.538
They need to feel protected
with the kind of ferocity

04:47.538 --> 04:50.040
only a mother can summon.

04:50.040 --> 04:51.041
[inhales]

04:53.335 --> 04:56.213
It's no matter if they were
born of my own...

04:56.713 --> 04:58.215
flesh.

04:59.800 --> 05:00.801
[inhales]

05:02.970 --> 05:05.180
Would I kill

05:05.180 --> 05:08.183
to protect a child in my charge?

05:08.892 --> 05:11.311
That is the question you have
for me, I assume, Detective?

05:11.311 --> 05:14.314
♪

05:16.275 --> 05:18.151
To that, I would say

05:18.151 --> 05:21.196
without so much as blinking,

05:21.196 --> 05:23.699
I would kill without compunction...

05:26.368 --> 05:29.872
for the sake and safety
of any child in my care.

05:34.459 --> 05:35.711
So,

05:37.045 --> 05:39.173
now, you have your answer.

05:41.717 --> 05:43.427
- Where have you been?

05:44.803 --> 05:47.181
♪

05:47.181 --> 05:48.223
- Um...

05:48.599 --> 05:51.393
CHARLES:
But when you finally do land your dream,

05:51.393 --> 05:53.812
your moment in that spotlight...

05:54.313 --> 05:56.565
- I said, where have you been?

05:58.650 --> 05:59.902
- Oh.

05:59.902 --> 06:03.030
CHARLES:
...how far would you go to hang onto it?

06:03.030 --> 06:05.240
- Oh! [gasps]

06:05.240 --> 06:06.950
Oh, thank you!

06:06.950 --> 06:10.495
Oh, thank you! [laughing] Oh, gosh!

06:10.495 --> 06:13.498
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

06:13.498 --> 06:16.502
♪ vocalizing ♪

06:56.542 --> 06:59.545
[applause, audience cheering]

06:59.545 --> 07:02.005
♪ eerie music playing ♪

07:02.005 --> 07:02.965
- Help me...

07:02.965 --> 07:05.133
[thud]
[audience gasping]

07:05.133 --> 07:07.219
OLIVER: Somebody! Anybody!
[shocked chatter]

07:07.761 --> 07:09.388
- He's not moving!

07:09.388 --> 07:11.390
WOMAN:
Ben! Call 911.

07:11.390 --> 07:14.184
MAN: I don't feel a pulse.
[sirens wailing]

07:14.184 --> 07:15.811
[sirens blare]
[street chatter]

07:16.353 --> 07:18.689
MAN: I'm trying to wrap my head
around it myself.

07:18.689 --> 07:20.065
No, don't you under--

07:20.065 --> 07:22.276
No, they already pronounced him!

07:22.276 --> 07:24.736
They pronounced him!

07:24.736 --> 07:28.240
- Was there any foam around his mouth?
Foaming would indicate poisoning.

07:28.240 --> 07:31.368
- I only saw blood. Mabel!
What are you doing?

07:31.368 --> 07:34.079
Could be natural causes
or one of those, uh, rupture things.

07:34.079 --> 07:35.873
- Charles, please! It's opening night,

07:35.873 --> 07:39.376
and a big star in the prime of his life
drops dead on stage?

07:39.376 --> 07:41.753
OLIVER: Oh, my God. Oh, my God.
Oh, my God. He's dead.

07:41.753 --> 07:44.173
He's dead. Ben's dead.
My leading man is dead!

07:44.173 --> 07:46.717
- Hey, it's not your fault, Oliver.
- No, that's right it's not my--

07:46.717 --> 07:48.427
What? Of course, it's not my fault!

07:48.427 --> 07:49.761
Okay, Howard,

07:49.761 --> 07:52.639
you go and tell everyone
that it's all gonna be fine.

07:52.639 --> 07:54.725
Tell them, uh,
that we'll gather back at my place

07:54.725 --> 07:56.977
for the opening night party I planned,

07:56.977 --> 07:58.729
where we'll just sort all of this out.

07:58.729 --> 08:00.731
- I really don't think people
are in a party mood right now--

08:00.731 --> 08:03.692
- Just do it, Howard! Do it!

08:03.692 --> 08:06.111
- Hey, Oliver.
- You okay, buddy?

08:06.111 --> 08:09.031
- Oh, my God.
Is this really happening?

08:09.031 --> 08:10.532
How did I get here?

08:10.532 --> 08:13.452
♪

08:13.452 --> 08:15.454
[door knocking]
[door opening]

08:16.914 --> 08:19.625
Is this really happening?
- Happy First Read-Through Day!

08:19.625 --> 08:21.543
- Am I really going back to Broadway?

08:21.543 --> 08:23.462
- I hope so. Why else would I be here?

08:23.462 --> 08:24.838
- To support, to give notes,

08:24.838 --> 08:27.174
to translate what the young people say
for Charles.

08:27.174 --> 08:30.469
And because who gets to see you anymore?
- True! It's nice to see you.

08:30.469 --> 08:33.597
- Well, you know,
we're all just so busy-busy,

08:33.597 --> 08:36.183
and, you know, who are we
without a homicide?

08:36.183 --> 08:38.352
- Oliver, I know you're nervous.

08:38.352 --> 08:40.604
I know your last Broadway show
was a disaster.

08:40.604 --> 08:42.356
[elevator opens]
Everyone knows it. The world knows it.

08:42.356 --> 08:45.859
- Fast forward, fast forward.
- But you, sir, are a talented young man.

08:45.859 --> 08:49.321
You have a gift for leadership. And when
you asked me to join this production, I--

08:49.321 --> 08:50.572
- Hold, please.

08:50.572 --> 08:51.615
[sloshing]

08:52.699 --> 08:55.118
I asked you?!
- Yes, you asked me!

08:55.619 --> 08:57.454
You know what? Forget it.
- Oh, no, no, no.

08:57.454 --> 09:00.541
Please wax poetic about
how I begged you to be in my play,

09:00.541 --> 09:03.544
even though you haven't been on stage
since men had to play all the women.

09:04.086 --> 09:05.087
- You don't need to explain.

09:05.087 --> 09:06.880
- In Shakespeare times,
men had to play the women.

09:06.880 --> 09:08.465
- Ah.
- Women weren't allowed.

09:08.465 --> 09:10.843
- It's a, a age joke.
- It's also a career joke.

09:10.843 --> 09:12.886
- And I loved it,
but can we talk about me now

09:12.886 --> 09:14.346
and how I cannot believe

09:14.346 --> 09:17.266
I'm going to be in
the same room as Ben Glenroy?

09:17.266 --> 09:19.768
Hair up or hair down?
Do you think he likes ears?

09:19.768 --> 09:21.895
- Mabel, actors are just people.

09:21.895 --> 09:23.856
Remember how nervous you were
to meet me at first?

09:23.856 --> 09:26.567
- I don't maybe remember that?
- Yeah, but now look at us.

09:27.192 --> 09:29.611
Hey, when we get there,
how do you wanna handle the entrances?

09:29.611 --> 09:32.072
Maybe you introduce me and then I come in?
- Introduce?

09:32.072 --> 09:35.576
This is a table read, Charles.
It's not The Donna Reed Show.

09:35.576 --> 09:36.952
Donna Reed was--
- It's not worth it.

09:36.952 --> 09:39.246
- Okay, now,
please do not start this journey

09:39.246 --> 09:40.956
by alienating all of your colleagues

09:40.956 --> 09:43.417
with some desperate attempt at peacocking.

09:43.417 --> 09:44.668
No peacocking!

09:45.669 --> 09:47.796
Oliver Putnam in da house!

09:47.796 --> 09:51.508
[applause, cheering]

09:51.508 --> 09:53.260
I have a question.

09:53.260 --> 09:55.762
Who wants to go to Broadway?

09:55.762 --> 09:58.807
[excited squeal]
[cheering]

09:58.807 --> 10:01.101
[whistling]
[scattered gasps]

10:01.101 --> 10:02.936
- We thank you for your attention.

10:02.936 --> 10:04.229
Brief anecdote.

10:04.229 --> 10:07.608
I remember when I auditioned
for Mr. Oliver Putnam

10:07.608 --> 10:09.735
for this very play.
- It's true.

10:09.735 --> 10:11.403
- Do you remember what
you said to me, Oliver?

10:11.403 --> 10:13.739
- I sure do. I said,

10:13.739 --> 10:16.200
"How about you be
my assistant, instead?"

10:16.200 --> 10:17.951
- [giggles] That's right.
- Yes.

10:17.951 --> 10:18.952
- Word for word.

10:18.952 --> 10:20.204
The floor is yours.

10:20.204 --> 10:22.164
- Thank you, Howard.
[scattered applause]

10:22.164 --> 10:23.290
Ah-- [nervous laugh]

10:23.290 --> 10:26.251
So our leading man is
running a skitch late,

10:26.251 --> 10:28.295
but let's go ahead and get started.

10:28.754 --> 10:31.757
I welcome you all...
to the world...

10:32.341 --> 10:33.717
of Death Rattle!

10:33.717 --> 10:36.053
[gasps, applause]

10:36.053 --> 10:37.721
- Oh, my God!
OLIVER: Yeah.

10:37.721 --> 10:40.265
A story of death

10:40.265 --> 10:42.226
that happens in a lighthouse

10:42.226 --> 10:44.686
in foggy upper Nova Scotia,

10:44.686 --> 10:47.564
where the only person in the room,
when the deaths occurred,

10:48.482 --> 10:50.067
is an infant child.

10:50.609 --> 10:53.779
Now, some may call this chestnut of a play

10:53.779 --> 10:55.572
a little dusty,

10:55.572 --> 10:57.741
uh, but of course,
I've been called that myself

10:57.741 --> 11:00.077
a few times, frankly. [laughs]
[all laughing]

11:00.077 --> 11:01.912
[blows, coughs]

11:01.912 --> 11:03.163
[laughter]

11:03.163 --> 11:05.457
When our amazing producer, Donna Demeo,

11:05.457 --> 11:07.668
first called me about--
- With Clifford.

11:07.668 --> 11:09.795
[nervous laugh]
My son, Cliff,

11:09.795 --> 11:13.507
who is making his first
solo producing effort here.

11:13.507 --> 11:15.050
[sighs]
But with me.

11:15.050 --> 11:17.052
[scattered applause]
CLIFF: Thanks, Mom. Thank you, thanks.

11:17.052 --> 11:20.138
I am so super excited
because, like your characters

11:20.138 --> 11:23.058
who are trapped in a hurricane
in a deadly lighthouse,

11:23.058 --> 11:25.477
we're gonna take Broadway by storm!

11:26.270 --> 11:29.356
[gasps, surprised chatter]

11:29.356 --> 11:31.525
- Wow!
DONNA: How about that?

11:31.525 --> 11:33.819
I'm so proud of my boy.

11:33.819 --> 11:36.196
So, so, so, so, so...

11:36.196 --> 11:37.406
[moans]

11:37.406 --> 11:38.782
proud. [giggles]

11:38.782 --> 11:41.326
He's gay, so I can kiss him like that.
[quiet squeal]

11:41.326 --> 11:43.120
[awkward chuckle, sniff]

11:44.079 --> 11:46.290
- Alrighty, then. So, I think that--

11:46.290 --> 11:48.500
[glass clinking]

11:48.500 --> 11:49.751
- What?

11:49.751 --> 11:51.253
Oh, I just like doing this.

11:51.253 --> 11:52.254
[laughter]

11:52.254 --> 11:54.298
No, no, if I may. Uh,

11:54.298 --> 11:57.092
we're in a very small room here,
and I'd like to address

11:57.092 --> 11:59.970
the show business elephant inside it,

11:59.970 --> 12:03.682
and that show business elephant is me.

12:03.682 --> 12:05.309
- Oh, dear lord.
CHARLES: Yes,

12:05.309 --> 12:06.768
I played Aristotle Brazzos

12:06.768 --> 12:09.313
in 224 episodes of dramatic television.

12:09.313 --> 12:10.856
- Aristotle?
- I can't.

12:10.856 --> 12:13.775
- As well as a reboot, uh,
which is currently on hiatus

12:13.775 --> 12:17.029
because the producer
is up on harassment charges.

12:17.029 --> 12:19.907
I also starred in
three made-for-TV movies,

12:19.907 --> 12:22.618
uh, and also a series of TV ads

12:22.618 --> 12:24.161
for the Dukakis campaign.

12:24.161 --> 12:25.913
All this is to say

12:25.913 --> 12:27.915
I'm just like you.

12:27.915 --> 12:29.208
I'm nobody special.

12:29.917 --> 12:31.585
I mean, I'm not any more special

12:31.585 --> 12:33.712
because, in a way, we're all...

12:33.712 --> 12:36.173
I think it was Gandhi who said,
"Isn't everyone, though, just--"

12:36.173 --> 12:38.467
- Thank you so much, Charles.
How inspiring.

12:38.467 --> 12:40.219
That was wonderful.
- Did I stick the landing?

12:40.219 --> 12:43.472
- The plane is literally
scattered across the runway.

12:43.472 --> 12:46.099
Alright then! As we await Ben,

12:46.099 --> 12:48.018
why don't we now take a look

12:48.018 --> 12:50.771
at the model for our set?

12:50.771 --> 12:53.065
♪

12:53.065 --> 12:55.943
[gasps, excited chatter]
[clapping]

12:55.943 --> 12:57.778
MABEL:
Okay, secret?

12:57.778 --> 12:59.863
I think theater is kinda lame.

13:00.989 --> 13:02.699
People all dressed up in costumes

13:02.699 --> 13:05.118
no real person would ever wear,

13:05.118 --> 13:07.204
acting like nobody's sitting out there

13:07.204 --> 13:09.873
watching them say things
no real person would ever say.

13:12.084 --> 13:15.587
But at least this piece of theater
is a murder mystery.

13:15.587 --> 13:17.214
That, I can get my head around.

13:17.214 --> 13:21.009
And every murder mystery needs a victim.

13:21.009 --> 13:23.178
- It really is--
- Okay!

13:23.178 --> 13:24.680
Okay!
[soft gasps]

13:25.597 --> 13:26.598
Who farted?

13:26.598 --> 13:29.017
[laughter]

13:29.017 --> 13:31.353
- Ben Glenroy, ladies and gentlemen!
- No, stop, stop, stop, stop!

13:31.353 --> 13:34.231
[applause, excited chatter]

13:34.231 --> 13:38.193
Thank you. Oh, by the way,
this is my manager, Dickie.

13:38.193 --> 13:40.946
He's not just my manager,
he's also my brother.

13:40.946 --> 13:42.865
But please don't say nepotism

13:42.865 --> 13:44.825
because he gets very
insecure about his abilities.

13:44.825 --> 13:45.826
- [laughs] Hi.

13:45.826 --> 13:47.578
BEN:
He's also the reason we're late.

13:47.578 --> 13:49.705
Dickie had us a, a block over.

13:49.705 --> 13:51.540
No way! You guys!

13:51.540 --> 13:53.625
This is my cast?
- Yes!

13:53.625 --> 13:56.962
Yes, and we are so thrilled!
- Hi. I'm Ben.

13:56.962 --> 13:59.298
I'm also trained as
an intimacy coordinator.

13:59.298 --> 14:00.507
- Hi, I'm Kimber,

14:00.507 --> 14:02.968
and I didn't realize
we had any love scenes.

14:02.968 --> 14:04.928
- What?
We're in the middle of one right now.

14:04.928 --> 14:06.972
- Oh. [laughs]
- Timber for Kimber.

14:06.972 --> 14:09.183
[Kimber giggling]
And you...

14:09.183 --> 14:12.936
are way too fuckin' handsome.
Somebody fire him, now!

14:12.936 --> 14:14.521
[laughter]
- I'm Ty.

14:14.521 --> 14:17.274
- Oh! If y'all would just
please quick sign these NDAs,

14:17.274 --> 14:19.985
and the last page telling us
you're okay with us filming.

14:19.985 --> 14:21.278
- I-I'm sorry, filming?

14:21.278 --> 14:23.447
- Yeah. Two, uh, shows
for the price of one.

14:23.447 --> 14:27.034
My Broadway debut, and a documentary
about my Broadway debut.

14:27.034 --> 14:30.787
This is my documentarian, Tobert.
You heard that right.

14:30.787 --> 14:32.247
- It's Robert with a T.

14:32.247 --> 14:34.082
Hey, Broadway, I am just an observer.

14:34.082 --> 14:36.210
This is literally the last time
you're gonna hear my voice.

14:36.210 --> 14:38.003
- Hello, Ben.
I'm Charles-Haden Savage.

14:38.003 --> 14:39.755
- Fuck me!
- Oh wow...

14:39.755 --> 14:42.549
- Oh, the energy coming from this corner!

14:42.549 --> 14:44.801
Am I right?
Do we all feel this?

14:44.801 --> 14:46.220
- Ben, this is our Nanny.

14:46.220 --> 14:48.055
- Loretta.
- Yeah.

14:48.055 --> 14:49.598
- Oliver tells me you're one
to look out for.

14:49.598 --> 14:52.226
- Oh, well, Oliver flatters.

14:52.226 --> 14:53.727
- Just don't upstage me.

14:54.645 --> 14:57.523
[laughs] I'm kidding. I'm kidding.

14:57.523 --> 14:59.858
No, I'm honored to work with you.
LORETTA: Oh my.

14:59.858 --> 15:02.152
Well, my friends
are just beside themselves

15:02.152 --> 15:04.112
that I'm gonna get to work with The CoBro.

15:04.112 --> 15:07.324
- Oh God, no, please. Just...
Just CoBro.

15:07.741 --> 15:09.284
- Sorry?
BEN: Yeah, no,

15:09.284 --> 15:11.411
the "the" makes me sound like an asshole.

15:11.411 --> 15:13.163
- Oh.
- Like the Rock.

15:13.163 --> 15:16.667
Or the Pope. I mean, come on,
get over yourselves. Right?

15:17.292 --> 15:19.711
But, in the films,
I'm just the friendly zoologist

15:19.711 --> 15:21.964
who morphs into a 20-foot cobra

15:21.964 --> 15:24.466
and helps the cops save the day.

15:25.133 --> 15:26.176
Hey, you.

15:28.136 --> 15:31.056
- Oh, hi. I loved you in Girl Cop.

15:31.056 --> 15:33.058
- Oh, that old thing?

15:34.643 --> 15:35.644
[blows]

15:35.644 --> 15:37.563
[Mabel giggling]
[Ben chuckles]

15:37.563 --> 15:39.731
- Alright, well, this is exciting.

15:39.731 --> 15:41.942
Shall we take our seats
and start the read?

15:41.942 --> 15:44.486
- Oh, yeah! Yeah, yeah! A read-through!
[excited chatter]

15:44.486 --> 15:46.572
I wanna read! Oh, hey, by the way.

15:46.572 --> 15:48.907
Thanks for the tip on Amy Schumer's place.

15:48.907 --> 15:50.701
Just moved in.
- Oh!

15:50.701 --> 15:53.203
- Tell her she left a bunch of
cottage cheese in the fridge.

15:53.203 --> 15:56.373
Fuck... Fuck... Fuckerballs. Fuck.

15:56.373 --> 15:58.500
Dickie? There's cookies here.

15:58.500 --> 16:01.503
- Oh no. Ben can't have cookies.

16:01.503 --> 16:03.922
He's on a very strict diet for CoBro,

16:03.922 --> 16:07.217
and cookies are [laughs] a weakness.

16:07.217 --> 16:09.595
- Well, not a weakness. I just...

16:10.596 --> 16:12.639
Where are they from?
- Schmackary's.

16:12.639 --> 16:15.142
- Oh... God, even the name is sexy.

16:15.142 --> 16:18.061
- I'll take them.
- No, it's fine, it's fine. Leave 'em.

16:18.061 --> 16:19.521
Leave 'em! Just...

16:19.521 --> 16:21.607
Let's read.
OLIVER: Alright!

16:21.607 --> 16:23.609
So, this is kind of exciting.

16:23.609 --> 16:25.694
Shall we begin, KT?

16:25.694 --> 16:27.154
- From the top, everyone.

16:27.154 --> 16:28.363
Ladies and gentlemen,

16:28.363 --> 16:31.825
I give you... page one.

16:31.825 --> 16:32.868
[sloshing]

16:32.868 --> 16:34.870
- I wasn't ready. [clears throat]

16:36.246 --> 16:38.957
[dramatically]
"It's a night in upper Nova Scotia."

16:38.957 --> 16:41.335
- Oh, hot damn!
That is a hot Schmackary.

16:42.961 --> 16:45.839
Sorry. I just had a corner.

16:45.839 --> 16:48.342
No more. It's alright.

16:48.342 --> 16:50.552
Reading.
[Howard clears throat]

16:50.552 --> 16:53.263
- "A detective makes his way
toward the audience.

16:53.263 --> 16:54.640
He is our narrator."

16:54.640 --> 16:57.893
- [deep voice] "What turned me
into a creature of the night?

16:57.893 --> 16:59.436
"Let me tell you.

16:59.436 --> 17:02.231
"I just finished up a case in Halifax
when I got a call

17:02.231 --> 17:06.193
"about some curious goings-on
at the old Pickwick Lighthouse.

17:06.193 --> 17:08.362
I made my way to see for myself."

17:08.362 --> 17:11.823
- "A lighthouse appears,
and a storm shelter door opens.

17:11.823 --> 17:14.826
A nanny emerges from the shelter."

17:15.702 --> 17:17.204
- [thick Scottish accent]
"Storm's comin'.

17:18.288 --> 17:21.333
Don't think it's a night
for roaming the rocks."

17:26.046 --> 17:29.174
- I-I'm sorry, I think I missed
some of those words.

17:29.174 --> 17:32.886
- Oh, I was trying a Scottish dialect.
OLIVER: Uh-huh.

17:33.887 --> 17:35.264
Because the nanny's...

17:35.264 --> 17:38.267
- The nanny refers to
a childhood in Aberdeen.

17:39.935 --> 17:40.978
- Right.

17:41.478 --> 17:43.063
LORETTA:
Um, or, or not.

17:43.063 --> 17:45.732
- No, no, no, no, no.
I-It's okay to try things.

17:45.732 --> 17:47.359
L-Let's just go again.

17:47.359 --> 17:50.362
- "A nanny emerges from the shelter."

17:50.737 --> 17:52.197
- [Québécois accent]
"Storm's coming.

17:52.739 --> 17:56.243
Don't think it's a night
for roaming on the rocks."

17:59.121 --> 18:00.414
French Canadian.

18:02.124 --> 18:04.543
Because it's up in the Maritimes there.

18:04.543 --> 18:07.504
So, a lot of French... I'm sorry.

18:07.504 --> 18:10.507
It's-- [laughs] This is my process.

18:10.507 --> 18:14.428
It's just how I... find the nanny's voice.

18:14.428 --> 18:15.429
OLIVER:
You know what?

18:15.429 --> 18:18.432
Maybe we try it slightly more
how you talk.

18:22.519 --> 18:24.438
- "A nanny emerges from the shelter."

18:24.980 --> 18:26.273
- Um...

18:26.273 --> 18:27.858
[flatly]
"Storm's coming.

18:28.817 --> 18:32.696
[sighs] Don't think it's a night
for roaming on the rocks."

18:32.696 --> 18:33.739
[inhales]

18:36.491 --> 18:37.701
- Um...

18:37.701 --> 18:39.328
"I don't go roaming anywhere."

18:55.010 --> 18:56.053
- [whispers]
It's you.

18:59.932 --> 19:02.643
- [gasps] Oh, my God, it's me!
[laughs] Oh, I'm so...

19:02.643 --> 19:03.644
[laughs]

19:03.644 --> 19:05.854
Oh, I'm sorry, it's me, isn't it?

19:05.854 --> 19:07.231
- I-It's your line, yes.

19:07.231 --> 19:09.274
- You know what?
I didn't highlight that one.

19:09.274 --> 19:10.609
I'm gonna do that right now.

19:10.609 --> 19:13.529
- Good. Now, you'll always have it...

19:13.529 --> 19:14.821
there 'cause it's highlighted.

19:14.821 --> 19:18.325
♪

19:18.325 --> 19:19.618
[quiet chatter]

19:19.618 --> 19:21.119
[Ben sighs]

19:21.119 --> 19:23.497
- [quietly]
Our nanny is a stinkeroony.

19:23.497 --> 19:25.332
- [quietly]
No, Ben, Ben, she'll be fine.

19:25.332 --> 19:27.167
She's just finding the voice.
You heard her.

19:27.167 --> 19:29.169
- Do you hear me, Oliver?

19:29.169 --> 19:31.338
She's a stinkeroony!
[sighs]

19:31.338 --> 19:33.423
I say give her the boo-tay before we...

19:33.423 --> 19:35.634
get too far down the road.
- No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

19:35.634 --> 19:38.595
Tru-- Just-- Loretta is very special.

19:38.595 --> 19:40.597
Just let me talk to her, okay?

19:40.597 --> 19:41.849
Just...

19:45.602 --> 19:48.605
Hello.
- Oh gosh, I'm so sorry. I'm...

19:49.273 --> 19:50.315
I get nervous

19:50.315 --> 19:52.818
and I'm not good at table reads.

19:53.443 --> 19:55.988
But, please, please don't give up on me.

19:56.488 --> 19:58.407
- Listen to me. Um...

19:58.407 --> 20:00.576
My first table read,

20:00.576 --> 20:02.995
there was a young actor,

20:02.995 --> 20:04.621
and he got very nervous,

20:04.621 --> 20:06.540
and he was missing lines,

20:06.540 --> 20:08.876
inaudible dialogue. It was painful.

20:08.876 --> 20:10.502
- [sighs] Yeah.

20:10.502 --> 20:12.504
- Everyone tells me to fire him

20:12.963 --> 20:14.464
but I refused.

20:15.382 --> 20:17.092
And you know who that young actor was?

20:17.718 --> 20:19.386
- No. No!

20:19.386 --> 20:21.847
- No one you'd know.
Everyone was right.

20:21.847 --> 20:24.224
He was a train wreck.
I fired him three weeks later.

20:25.267 --> 20:26.894
But you are not that.

20:26.894 --> 20:29.021
You are the opposite of that.

20:30.147 --> 20:32.482
And anyone who has not seen that yet

20:33.108 --> 20:36.195
is either dumb, blind,
or a combination of the two.

20:36.195 --> 20:38.197
[giggles]
You go,

20:38.989 --> 20:40.115
I go.

20:40.115 --> 20:41.658
- Oh, Oliver, gosh...

20:41.658 --> 20:43.160
- You go,

20:44.286 --> 20:45.495
I go.

20:46.747 --> 20:48.290
Okay?
[sighs]

20:48.290 --> 20:49.958
♪

20:49.958 --> 20:52.044
- Thank you. Thank you.

20:52.044 --> 20:54.213
- Okay. Alright.
[sniffles]

20:54.963 --> 20:57.257
Oh, my God, Loretta. Where is Loretta?

20:57.257 --> 20:59.551
- Loretta is in her dressing room.
She is pretty upset,

20:59.551 --> 21:01.845
but she said she'll try
to make the... party.

21:01.845 --> 21:04.765
- Okay.
- Are you sure a party is a...

21:04.765 --> 21:06.517
you know...
- What?

21:06.517 --> 21:08.936
No, no, no, no. Spit it out, Charles.

21:08.936 --> 21:12.648
Heap some more suffering
onto my already full plate!

21:13.232 --> 21:16.235
There might be a little room
next to the despair!

21:16.235 --> 21:18.695
♪

21:18.695 --> 21:21.406
- Party sounds nice.
[panting, growls]

21:25.744 --> 21:26.995
Party...

21:26.995 --> 21:29.831
♪

21:31.667 --> 21:33.752
LESTER:
Shouldn't be too much longer, people!

21:33.752 --> 21:35.671
Patience, people, patience!

21:35.671 --> 21:37.548
UMA:
Ugh. This is ridiculous.

21:37.548 --> 21:40.634
- Safety first. Don't worry.
It's all good. We'll get there.

21:40.634 --> 21:44.012
Uma, I promise you, I'll get you in.
I promise.

21:44.012 --> 21:46.473
- What's going on?
LESTER: We'll get there, don't worry.

21:46.473 --> 21:47.766
- The elevator's out.
- Ugh!

21:47.766 --> 21:49.935
- Got them working overtime on it.
Should be up and running soon.

21:49.935 --> 21:53.605
- Okay, listen, guys--
- The press is already up my ass.

21:53.605 --> 21:56.859
We need to get a statement out.
- "Ben Glenroy" is trending on Twitter.

21:56.859 --> 21:59.736
So is "RIP Ben Glenroy."
So is "Ben Dead."

21:59.736 --> 22:02.823
So is... "Real Housewives"?
Oh, my God, was tonight the reunion?

22:02.823 --> 22:03.824
- Yeah, listen.

22:03.824 --> 22:06.785
This is the moment
where producers really matter.

22:06.785 --> 22:09.955
Just because Ben is dead,
doesn't mean the show has to die, too.

22:09.955 --> 22:11.582
- Oliver, you're in shock.

22:11.582 --> 22:13.667
The fact this happened in the Goosebury,

22:13.667 --> 22:16.461
the same theater as your Splash...

22:16.461 --> 22:19.256
[growls]
I'm not saying you're cursed,

22:19.256 --> 22:21.049
but it wouldn't surprise me
if you pissed off

22:21.049 --> 22:23.677
a witch or two in a previous life.
[growls]

22:23.677 --> 22:25.971
- Only seven at a time
allowed in the one that's working.

22:25.971 --> 22:28.473
- And tenants have priority status!

22:28.473 --> 22:31.268
- Along with the hosts of the saddest
opening night party in history!

22:31.268 --> 22:32.978
♪

22:32.978 --> 22:34.813
LESTER:
That's it! That's it.

22:35.564 --> 22:37.149
DONNA: 10?
OLIVER: Yes.

22:37.149 --> 22:38.775
- At least you had the consideration

22:38.775 --> 22:41.195
to keep the body out of
the building this time.

22:41.195 --> 22:43.447
- You always know just what to say, Uma.

22:43.447 --> 22:45.449
- It's a goddamn gift.

22:46.325 --> 22:49.328
[quiet party chatter]
[plates, glasses clinking]

22:49.328 --> 22:52.331
♪ soft music playing ♪

22:53.540 --> 22:54.541
[KT gasps]

22:57.044 --> 22:58.545
JONATHAN:
Oh, man.

22:59.505 --> 23:02.174
Oh, you're using Ben's opening night gift.

23:02.174 --> 23:03.800
- Yeah, didn't think I'd need it so soon.

23:05.886 --> 23:07.221
- It really is a beautiful gift.

23:08.138 --> 23:10.641
- I didn't realize
assistants got one, too.

23:11.141 --> 23:12.976
How very generous of Ben.

23:12.976 --> 23:15.562
- And I didn't realize
stage managers wiped their nose

23:15.562 --> 23:17.648
with anything other than
the bottom of their palm.

23:17.648 --> 23:19.316
- You've got crumbs in your beard.

23:19.316 --> 23:22.152
- ♪ And let's reach for stars... ♪

23:25.113 --> 23:28.116
OLIVER: Oh, great. Let's just leave
all the cellophane on the food.

23:29.201 --> 23:31.245
- Hey, Oliver. How you holding up?

23:31.703 --> 23:33.413
- I just ate a dinner roll.

23:33.413 --> 23:34.957
- Wow, that bad?

23:34.957 --> 23:38.168
- The lead of my play
left my stage without a pulse,

23:38.168 --> 23:40.170
and all I can think about is my career.

23:41.797 --> 23:43.632
I don't know, Mabel.

23:43.632 --> 23:46.343
Narcissism should really
be more fun than this.

23:47.344 --> 23:50.722
Maybe I am cursed.
- Well, shit, Oliver.

23:50.722 --> 23:51.723
[sighs]

23:52.349 --> 23:55.185
My first thought when he went down?

23:55.185 --> 23:56.687
Maybe he was poisoned.

23:57.479 --> 24:01.483
And a podcast about the poisoning
of a big movie star?

24:01.483 --> 24:03.694
That could be big.

24:03.694 --> 24:06.780
And maybe with their play shut down,

24:06.780 --> 24:08.991
and a new podcast in motion,

24:08.991 --> 24:12.202
maybe I could spend more time
with my guys again.

24:14.705 --> 24:16.164
- Me more than him, right?

24:16.164 --> 24:18.458
- I don't pick favorite olds.

24:20.043 --> 24:21.336
- Better to leave it unsaid.

24:22.045 --> 24:23.046
[knowing growl]

24:23.046 --> 24:24.882
[knocking on door]

24:27.384 --> 24:29.386
[sighs]
- How you doing, Charlie?

24:29.386 --> 24:32.306
Aw...
- Oh. Traumatized, uh, perplexed.

24:32.306 --> 24:34.391
[quietly]
Am I allowed to say relieved?

24:34.391 --> 24:36.810
I mean, my nerves couldn't
take eight shows a week.

24:36.810 --> 24:38.228
But don't tell Oliver I said that.

24:38.228 --> 24:41.231
- Oh, I'm a steel trap... Oh, Charlie.
[sighs]

24:41.231 --> 24:44.234
It's okay to be relieved
that the show is over.

24:44.985 --> 24:46.904
Means more time for us.

24:46.904 --> 24:49.990
- It does.
Hey, did you get Lucy home alright?

24:49.990 --> 24:51.992
- Yeah. That girl's a lot.

24:51.992 --> 24:53.911
I'm ready to get trashed.

24:53.911 --> 24:57.331
♪ soft piano music playing ♪

24:57.331 --> 24:59.499
[quiet party chatter]

24:59.499 --> 25:02.878
♪

25:05.130 --> 25:06.715
- I didn't know you tinkered.

25:06.715 --> 25:08.842
- Oh, I tinker.

25:08.842 --> 25:10.219
[Oliver chuckles]

25:10.219 --> 25:12.054
- Keep tinkering.

25:12.054 --> 25:15.390
- ♪ And the dearest love ♪

25:15.390 --> 25:18.268
♪ In all the world ♪

25:18.644 --> 25:21.813
♪ Is waiting somewhere ♪

25:21.813 --> 25:24.107
♪ For me ♪

25:24.107 --> 25:26.652
BOTH: ♪ Is waiting ♪

25:26.652 --> 25:29.238
♪ Somewhere ♪

25:29.238 --> 25:32.741
♪ Somewhere for ♪

25:32.741 --> 25:36.703
♪ Me... ♪

25:37.371 --> 25:38.539
♪ stops playing ♪

25:38.539 --> 25:40.165
[both giggle]

25:40.165 --> 25:43.210
- I feel better now. How about you?

25:43.210 --> 25:45.671
- Good as new.
[laughs]

25:45.671 --> 25:48.674
Hey. Can you look at the [sighs]

25:48.674 --> 25:52.010
back of my earring?
Is the thing snapped into the thing?

25:52.010 --> 25:53.846
- Are these technical terms?
- No. [sighs]

25:53.846 --> 25:57.140
I just had to get
outta my costume so fast,

25:57.140 --> 25:58.684
I'm not sure I hooked it in right.

25:58.684 --> 26:01.562
- Wouldn't you know it?
The thing is in the thing.

26:01.562 --> 26:03.605
- Good.
[Oliver sighs]

26:03.605 --> 26:05.941
- Thank you for making me feel lighter.

26:06.900 --> 26:08.318
If only for a minute.

26:08.861 --> 26:10.571
Oh God. [sighs]

26:11.405 --> 26:13.407
I wanted tonight to happen.

26:14.741 --> 26:16.243
For both of us, most of all.

26:17.327 --> 26:18.328
[sighs]

26:19.037 --> 26:21.123
- Well [inhales, exhales]

26:21.123 --> 26:23.000
the show may be over

26:24.168 --> 26:26.503
but doesn't that mean

26:26.503 --> 26:29.840
we're not obliged to live
by your show rule anymore?

26:31.175 --> 26:32.176
♪

26:32.176 --> 26:34.178
The one that keeps things...

26:34.761 --> 26:36.263
professional...

26:36.722 --> 26:39.850
[laughs] and platonic?

26:39.850 --> 26:41.268
♪

26:41.268 --> 26:42.436
[door opening]

26:42.436 --> 26:45.147
BEN: Okay! Okay!
[crowd gasping, screaming]

26:45.147 --> 26:46.398
Who farted?!

26:46.398 --> 26:48.358
[crowd gasping]

26:48.358 --> 26:50.569
Mama's back, bitches!

26:50.569 --> 26:53.071
That's right. I'm alive!

26:53.071 --> 26:55.449
CHARLES: H-How could you-- What?
MABEL: What the fuck?

26:55.449 --> 26:57.201
[Ben sighs, pants]

26:57.201 --> 26:58.785
- I was dead, dude.

26:58.785 --> 27:02.581
For, like, an hour. They said it was
like a record in their hospital.

27:02.581 --> 27:05.000
Right, Dickie?
- Oh, they didn't say anything like that.

27:05.000 --> 27:07.586
- They pumped my stomach.
I barfed up a ton.

27:07.586 --> 27:09.755
I don't know.
They said maybe it was something I ate?

27:09.755 --> 27:11.840
- But y-you had blood in your mouth!

27:11.840 --> 27:15.260
- Yeah. Well, I bit the fuck
outta my tongue when I fell.

27:15.260 --> 27:16.512
I don't feel it now, though.

27:17.596 --> 27:18.597
[heaves]

27:18.597 --> 27:20.057
[crowd murmuring]

27:20.057 --> 27:21.725
[heaves]

27:21.725 --> 27:23.143
[gags] Oh, sorry.

27:23.143 --> 27:26.021
The nurses-- oh, my God.
They were so freaked out.

27:26.021 --> 27:27.648
The doctors were like,
"Do not go anywhere!"

27:27.648 --> 27:29.816
But I had to get back to see you guys!

27:29.816 --> 27:31.318
My cast. My...

27:32.402 --> 27:33.445
[phone recording]
I just...

27:37.950 --> 27:39.576
Oh, wow!

27:39.576 --> 27:40.994
Sorry! [sniffles]

27:40.994 --> 27:43.789
Shit! I did not expect to get emotional!

27:43.789 --> 27:45.707
But, when I was dead, guys?

27:46.959 --> 27:48.460
I saw the light.

27:48.460 --> 27:51.046
That light, yes. The dead person light.

27:51.588 --> 27:52.840
I saw it.

27:54.341 --> 27:57.386
And I saw all the shit
that I pulled with all of you

27:57.386 --> 27:58.929
over these last few months.

27:58.929 --> 28:00.931
And I thought, I can't die like this.

28:02.599 --> 28:06.019
And so, I'm back,
and I'm gonna be so much better.

28:06.019 --> 28:09.106
And we are going to
kick ass with this show.

28:09.106 --> 28:11.608
You hear me, Oliver?
- Oh, my God.

28:12.568 --> 28:14.611
You're really alive...

28:16.113 --> 28:17.614
and so soft.

28:18.407 --> 28:19.449
[both sigh]

28:20.075 --> 28:21.118
[snorts]

28:21.910 --> 28:23.579
- Kimber...

28:23.579 --> 28:25.289
[heavy breathing]

28:25.289 --> 28:28.292
I'm so sorry I made
everything messy between us.

28:29.168 --> 28:30.502
I fucked up.

28:31.420 --> 28:32.921
But I'm gonna make it right.

28:32.921 --> 28:34.882
♪

28:34.882 --> 28:37.593
Ty. Forgive me, please, for...

28:38.510 --> 28:40.929
getting so mad at you
for wanting to use my trainer.

28:40.929 --> 28:43.140
It's just, Hutch is my secret weapon.

28:43.140 --> 28:45.225
And, you know,
there's no shot you can afford him,

28:45.225 --> 28:47.728
but I-I suppose I could
give you his digits.

28:49.104 --> 28:50.355
Jonathan.

28:51.523 --> 28:52.774
Jonathan!

28:54.151 --> 28:55.527
My understudy.

28:55.527 --> 28:57.404
[laughs] When this started,

28:57.404 --> 28:59.823
I was never gonna let you
ever step foot on that stage,

28:59.823 --> 29:01.658
but, moving forward,

29:02.326 --> 29:03.702
I'm gonna consider it.

29:03.702 --> 29:05.370
Maybe a Wednesday matinee!

29:05.370 --> 29:08.665
- Let's not over-promise here.
BEN: Ha, Donna!

29:08.665 --> 29:10.667
My beloved producer!

29:11.126 --> 29:12.628
You and your...

29:14.254 --> 29:16.256
boy.
- It's Cliff.

29:16.256 --> 29:19.760
- I know. That's what I said.
Look, um... [sighs]

29:20.594 --> 29:22.596
I know I haven't been easy to deal with,

29:22.596 --> 29:24.056
with all my complaints about...

29:24.515 --> 29:26.266
the... size of my dressing room,

29:26.266 --> 29:28.352
and the... shape of my dressing room,

29:28.352 --> 29:30.145
and the color palette of my dressing room.

29:30.145 --> 29:32.981
Basically, everything
I've ever said about my...

29:32.981 --> 29:34.775
unnecessarily shitty dressing room.

29:34.775 --> 29:36.235
I take it all back.

29:36.235 --> 29:37.778
Uh-- [sighs]

29:37.778 --> 29:39.613
I'm really so sorry, Donna.

29:39.613 --> 29:40.948
And I'm so sorry, boy.

29:40.948 --> 29:43.200
- Cliff.
- Right. [sighs]

29:43.951 --> 29:46.370
Would be great if we could
fix up my dressing room, by the way.

29:46.370 --> 29:49.081
It's the last time I'm gonna
mention anything, alright?

29:49.081 --> 29:50.874
Pinky swear. Bobo!

29:50.874 --> 29:53.418
Look at-- Bobo. You know what?
You're s-- [sighs]

29:53.418 --> 29:55.128
You're such a funny guy

29:55.128 --> 29:58.298
and a-all I ever do is say no to you.

29:58.298 --> 29:59.550
But I promise you.

30:00.509 --> 30:02.135
No more no-nos for Bobo.

30:02.135 --> 30:03.887
♪

30:03.887 --> 30:05.556
KT, my bad

30:05.556 --> 30:08.100
for accusing you of stealing my mangoes.

30:08.100 --> 30:10.811
Ataulfo season is really short,
and it's pretty much the only fruit

30:10.811 --> 30:12.437
I can eat on the CoBro Diet.

30:12.437 --> 30:15.023
- I know it was coming
from a place of love.

30:15.023 --> 30:17.025
- It wasn't, but thank you.

30:19.820 --> 30:21.238
Oh.

30:21.238 --> 30:23.866
And Loretta. [weak laugh]

30:24.283 --> 30:25.993
The consummate professional!

30:25.993 --> 30:28.745
♪

30:28.745 --> 30:30.163
But...

30:31.331 --> 30:33.625
CoBro knows a fellow snake
when he sees one.

30:34.918 --> 30:38.297
[long hiss]

30:40.090 --> 30:40.966
[short hiss]

30:43.093 --> 30:45.012
And Charles!
- Oh, don't worry about me!

30:45.012 --> 30:48.599
You can skip me! I get it!
You're a new man, which is exciting.

30:49.892 --> 30:52.060
- You and I never
got off on the right foot.

30:52.060 --> 30:53.854
CHARLES: Nope.
- And if anyone here was happy

30:53.854 --> 30:57.566
that I was maybe dead,
I bet it was you.

30:58.192 --> 30:59.651
- Yeah.
- I know you don't have

30:59.651 --> 31:02.613
many more years left
to hone your craft.

31:02.613 --> 31:05.073
And I get that every day counts.

31:05.073 --> 31:07.826
And after this experience,
I really get it now.

31:07.826 --> 31:09.077
So,

31:09.828 --> 31:11.246
to starting over?

31:12.956 --> 31:14.458
- To starting over.

31:15.959 --> 31:18.879
[phone ringing]
DICKIE: Ben, you gotta take this.

31:18.879 --> 31:21.840
- What? Oh.
Ben's gotta take this. [scoffs]

31:22.841 --> 31:24.551
Oh. Um...
[silences phone]

31:24.551 --> 31:26.553
Yeah, I'll go somewhere quieter.

31:27.513 --> 31:30.974
Guys! I'm gonna go
up to my apartment and crash,

31:30.974 --> 31:33.227
shower up,
maybe shake off the cobwebs,

31:33.227 --> 31:35.020
but I'll see you this week, alright?

31:35.020 --> 31:36.522
Death Rattle lives!

31:36.522 --> 31:39.024
[confused murmuring]

31:39.024 --> 31:40.234
CLIFF:
Wow.

31:40.234 --> 31:41.735
Word is out. Ben is back.

31:41.735 --> 31:43.612
[door opens, shuts]

31:43.612 --> 31:46.740
- It's a hell of a story to
reopen a play with, people.

31:46.740 --> 31:48.116
[quiet murmuring]

31:48.116 --> 31:49.910
- So we're back.

31:49.910 --> 31:51.912
We're all back on Broadway!

31:51.912 --> 31:54.581
♪

31:54.581 --> 31:57.167
[hesitant chatter]
[scattered applause]

31:57.167 --> 32:00.295
- Congrats. You must be thrilled.
- Mm.

32:00.295 --> 32:02.756
- I said you must be thrilled.

32:02.756 --> 32:04.758
- Ben may be back,

32:04.758 --> 32:06.343
but it doesn't change the fact

32:06.343 --> 32:09.137
that he is a fucking asshole.

32:12.516 --> 32:14.560
♪

32:16.937 --> 32:19.022
[keys jingling, lock clicking]

32:19.022 --> 32:20.023
[door unlocking]

32:21.567 --> 32:23.068
[light switch clicks]

32:23.068 --> 32:25.195
[sighs]

32:25.195 --> 32:28.198
♪

32:53.182 --> 32:56.185
[quiet street noise outside]

33:00.647 --> 33:03.650
[texting]

33:08.113 --> 33:09.156
[sends text]

33:10.407 --> 33:11.992
CHARLES:
I don't know what to make of any of it.

33:11.992 --> 33:14.453
Dead, not dead. Show, no show.
[Oliver sighs, sniffs]

33:14.453 --> 33:17.122
- Wait, so you're just gonna reopen
the show as if nothing happened?

33:17.122 --> 33:18.749
- Oh, please. Are you kidding?

33:18.749 --> 33:21.502
Donna and Cliff are gonna
make a meal out of what happened.

33:21.502 --> 33:23.712
Are you excited, friend? [laughs]
- Yeah!

33:23.712 --> 33:26.673
Eight shows a week! Trouper!
[sighs]

33:26.673 --> 33:30.052
OLIVER: Oh, I forgot to ask you.
Whatever happened to Joy's crazy aunt?

33:30.052 --> 33:32.054
- Oh, she broke up
with the hair transplant guy.

33:32.054 --> 33:33.430
- Oh, that's a shock.

33:33.430 --> 33:36.433
Oh, and did her brother ever find out
who sent the vulgar placemats?

33:36.433 --> 33:38.685
- Yeah, Ron.
- Ron, the guy with the chin?

33:38.685 --> 33:42.189
- Guys, this is not fair!
You hang out all the time.

33:42.189 --> 33:45.734
I wanna know about
Joy's crazy aunt and... Ron.

33:45.734 --> 33:46.860
- No, no, no.
- Oh, Ron's insane.

33:46.860 --> 33:47.903
You don't wanna know about him.

33:47.903 --> 33:50.864
- Well, let me know
if he makes more placemats.

33:50.864 --> 33:52.616
Just don't forget about me.

33:53.158 --> 33:55.077
CHARLES: Huh?
- What does that mean?

33:55.077 --> 33:57.704
- You know, I can't get over
what you've done with this place.

33:57.704 --> 33:59.081
MABEL:
Yeah, I know.

33:59.081 --> 34:01.083
That's what the people
who bought it said, too.

34:02.876 --> 34:04.378
OLIVER:
What?

34:04.378 --> 34:06.547
Your aunt sold the apartment?
[shuts door]

34:06.547 --> 34:08.257
- I have to be out in four weeks.

34:08.257 --> 34:09.800
- Seriously?
- You're leaving the Arconia?

34:09.800 --> 34:12.219
- I know, I know, but it's...
[Oliver sighs]

34:12.219 --> 34:15.222
it's time.
I mean, I need to get my own life.

34:16.265 --> 34:18.725
And you can come visit me in Brooklyn.

34:18.725 --> 34:20.727
Or maybe Queens?

34:22.062 --> 34:23.689
I'll come to you.

34:24.940 --> 34:27.943
OLIVER: The most important part
of chasing a dream

34:27.943 --> 34:30.362
is the people who chase
alongside with you.

34:30.362 --> 34:32.197
- So I was checking our message boards

34:32.197 --> 34:34.700
on our podcast site the other day,

34:34.700 --> 34:37.327
and people were
wondering where we'd been.

34:37.327 --> 34:39.079
It's kinda nice to be missed.

34:39.079 --> 34:41.373
- Yeah, it is nice.
- Yeah, it is. It is nice.

34:41.373 --> 34:43.584
Those who look beyond the doubters

34:43.584 --> 34:46.003
and choose to believe
your dream will happen...

34:46.003 --> 34:48.005
[elevator dings]
...all in good time.

34:48.005 --> 34:51.008
♪

34:51.925 --> 34:55.095
- I guess they fixed the elevator?
OLIVER: Hm.

34:55.095 --> 34:57.097
- [clears throat] Should we take it?

34:58.348 --> 34:59.766
I'm sort of nervous to take it.

34:59.766 --> 35:02.644
It's been just a gaping hole
for how many hours now?

35:03.812 --> 35:05.564
- Hey. If there's one thing I know,

35:07.441 --> 35:09.443
it's that we're good
at living on the edge.

35:13.864 --> 35:15.657
OLIVER:
Those who will go with you

35:15.657 --> 35:18.202
to help make that moment
when you finally arrive

35:18.202 --> 35:20.787
in your own big spotlight...

35:20.787 --> 35:23.415
[elevator creaking loudly]

35:23.415 --> 35:25.834
[metal grinding]

35:25.834 --> 35:28.504
[grinding fades, buzzing]

35:28.504 --> 35:30.589
...they're the only ones who matter.

35:31.548 --> 35:34.176
- You know, Mabel, w-we couldn't have done
the podcast anyway

35:34.176 --> 35:36.261
because Ben didn't die in the building.

35:40.182 --> 35:42.017
[liquid dripping]

35:42.017 --> 35:45.020
♪ suspenseful music playing ♪

35:45.020 --> 35:46.980
[dripping continues]

35:46.980 --> 35:48.941
- Wait. What's that?

35:48.941 --> 35:50.651
- Hm?

35:54.071 --> 35:57.032
[dripping increases]

35:57.032 --> 36:00.035
♪

36:00.035 --> 36:03.872
[metal creaking]

36:03.872 --> 36:06.083
[glass cracking]

36:06.083 --> 36:07.084
[elevator dings]

36:09.211 --> 36:11.547
[crash]
[Uma screams]

36:15.926 --> 36:18.470
- You gotta be fuckin' kidding me.

36:20.973 --> 36:22.432
♪ music swells ♪

36:22.432 --> 36:23.517
[Oliver growls]

36:24.059 --> 36:27.062
♪
